[C++ Program to Implement Bubble Sort Algorithm]

Bubble sort is a simple sorting algorithm that repeatedly steps through the list, compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are in the wrong order. The pass through the list is repeated until the list is sorted.

The basic idea of bubble sort is: iteratively step through the list, compare adjacent elements and swap them if they are in the wrong order. This ensures that by the end of each iteration the largest (or smallest) element “bubbles” to the top (or bottom) of the list.

Here's a C++ program implementing bubble sort algorithm:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
   bool swapped = false;       // flag to check if any swap is made in inner loop
   for (int I = 0; I <= n-2; i++) {
      swapped = false;          // assume that no swap is made
      for(int j = 0; j <= n-i-2; j++) {
         if(arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {    // check if left element is greater than right element
            int temp = arr[j];        // store the value of left element in temporary variable
            arr[j] = arr[j+1];       // assign the value of right element to left element
            arr[j+1] = temp;          // assign the value of temporary variable to right element
            swapped = true;           // set flag to true, as swap is made in inner loop
         }
      }
      if(swapped == false) {       // if no swap is made in inner loop, then array is sorted and exit from outer loop
         break;
      }
   }
}

int main() {
   int arr[] = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};    // input array to be sorted using bubble sort
   int n = sizeof(arr)/sizeof(arr[0]);          // find the size of the input array
   bubbleSort(arr, n);                           // pass the input array and its size to bubbleSort() function
   cout << "Sorted Array: ";                         // print sorted array
   for (int I = 0; I < n; i++) {                      // loop through the sorted array and print each element separately
      cout << arr[i] << " ";
   }
   return 0;
}
```

This implementation is based on recursive bubble sort algorithm. The time complexity of this implementation is O(n^2), which is quite high, as it involves nested loops to compare adjacent elements and swap them if required. In practical applications, efficient algorithms such as Quicksort and MergeSort are preferred over Bubble Sort due to their lower time complexity.

In Python:

```python
def bubbleSort(arr):
    n = len(arr)

    # flag to check if any swap is made in inner loop
    swapped = True

    while swapped:
        swapped = False
        for i in range(0, n-1):
            if arr[i] > arr[i+1]:
                # store the value of left element in temporary variable
                temp = arr[i]
                # assign the value of right element to left element
                arr[i] = arr[i+1]
                # assign the value of temporary variable to right element
                arr[i+1] = temp
                swapped = True

    return arr

arr = [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90] # input array to be sorted using bubbleSort() function
print("Sorted Array: ", end="")
for I in range(len(arr)):
    print(bubbleSort(arr)[i], end=" ")
```

The time complexity of this implementation is O(n^2) as well, due to nested loops involved. However, it's much simpler and easy-to-understand than the C++ implementation, making it a better choice for beginners or simple applications where speed isn't critical. For larger input sizes, recursive implementations are preferred over iterative ones due to their lower memory usage.

In terms of efficiency, MergeSort has a time complexity of O(n log n) which is much better than bubble sort. Quicksort also has the same time complexity but requires more complex logic and partitioning steps compared to MergeSort. Therefore, for practical applications, it's recommended to use efficient algorithms such as MergeSort or Quicksort instead of bubble sort due to their lower time complexity and higher efficiency.

In both C++ and Python implementations, the basic concept of bubble sort algorithm is same - iteratively compare adjacent elements and swap them if required until the array is sorted. The main difference lies in the syntax and language constructs used to represent the logic and algorithms. 

